segments.text: Fort Allbritton was a new member at that time.
All right, let's back up to coeducation.
Fort Allbritton was on in 73 because he was the one who was in particular.
When the proposal about coeducation, non-compulsory core came up,
do you have any idea what Mr. Rutter's initial reaction was?
Do you have any idea whether he was for it or when it first came up?
I would say Mr. Rutter probably wouldn't have expressed his initial reaction.
I never heard any remark with it at all.
But he was a very good decision-making type of person.
He was the type of person that he maybe couldn't run all the alternatives to his mind at one time,
but he could run enough through the decision and maybe it was pretty healthy.
Let's see, let's go back to Austin.
Which governors were most supportive of the work of the engineering
and the administration of the state of Austin?
Extension Service.
I'd say Dolph Briscoe.
Dolph Briscoe.
The reason I'm saying that, Dolph Conner.
Other than local legislators, were there any other legislators that were key supporters?
Yes.
Who?
Senator.
All right.
Do you remember his first name?
I don't.
Grant.
Grant Jones, that's right.
Any others?
Over the state?
Mm-hmm.
I can't call their names right now.
I'll tell you, I have that thing.
Whenever we had a budget, whenever they had the legislature,
it was the House Appropriations Committee.
I made it important that each one of them not only know me, but know my program.
I didn't work with the higher education committees.
I brought in all the new higher education.
But I made sure that everybody on the Appropriations Committee knew me.
And at that time, we all used to make presentations before they cut that out.
They had this little representative from down in New Orleans, Falls County, whatever it is.
He got to be a pretty good friend of mine, but that's good.
I saw his name.
The paper's a lobbyist now, by the way.
Mm-hmm.
Do you remember reading one of those?
They all get to be lobbyists.
Yeah.
He was very much supportive, I think.
Then we had a representative out of one of those Dallas towns, one of Cedar Hill, I don't know.
But he was a volunteer for us, so he was very supportive.
But I didn't know him very well.
As you look back, what were your proudest moments with the Extension Service?
The highlight events that you now remember.
I guess the highlight, the things that I enjoyed most about it,
the ability that we had complaints about our work over 19 years I was there.
But my really highlights was, I figured that when you take an organization with 15 employees,
you end up with 400, you own a self-support base of a million and a half,
and you get it up to 39 million.
And we carried, when I left that thing, I left over 13 million in reserves.
Mm, that's great.
Okay.
Now, let's turn to the amusing side.
Can you think of some event that happened that was one of those Texas, unbelievable,
something that maybe just went wrong, something just, the electricity went off?
It was one of those, I know you won't believe this, but it really happened?
No, I have one.
Okay.
I always had a State of the Union speech.
We always had an annual conference, and I always gave a State of the Union message,
okay?
I always stressed the basics.
And, of course, I had to, for some reason, I had to.
I wasn't even close to the one I was talking about in front of all 400 people, you know.
So they had a good laugh?
They all had a good laugh.
And, of course, I come back at them, and I said, now, Clara, the reason I did that, I just want to see it.
Okay.
Now, from all of your Aggie memories, either as a student, an employee, give me a funny Aggie story,
and then maybe a sad.
Okay.
Or a poignant Aggie story.
It could involve anything, anybody.
Well, the saddest one, I can get that right off my chest.
My roommate was in college.
And you all were roommates for how long?
Two years.
Two years.
But we was in the same outfit.
Okay.
Now some good Aggie fun.
This is the biggest Aggie fun.
Thanksgiving game in 1940, we made a touchdown, 7-0, 30-40 seconds of play.
We all hitchhiked into Austin.
And my roommate at that time also was from O.T.
Road.
Which was about five or six of us, but downhearted, didn't mention it anymore.
But anyway, we got out on Congress Avenue and started hitchhiking.
We got picked up, right off, two cars, one stopped, another stopped right behind us.
One had this Model 8 Ford with the little rumble seat in the back.
I don't remember, I was in the rumble seat in the back.
And they kept going out to Congress Avenue, you know, we told them, we don't want to get on the highway too late.
But it was great, and they took us out about 10 miles out of town, and I'll bet you there was five other University of Texas people out there and about 50 Aggies.
And they would eat the hell out of us.
With a paddle?
No, with a fish.
Oh, oh, oh.
And that was quite funny.
The reason that was funny, you think you're so damn stupid that you can get in a car like that.
And the other one pertains to your Rice University group.
Uh-oh, my freshman year, you know, we used to rent these cattle trailers to take us down to the court room.
And so, our upperclassmen told us that they wanted us to...
to all get together, freshmen, there was a whole bunch of us to get together as freshmen, and have Yelp practice right there at the entrance of the Rice Gate.
Well, four of the five of us, we got out there early, and we was standing there, and all at once, about damn 15 or 20 of these damn Rice Owls come out and grab us,
take us up to the damn dormitory room, and paint a damn heart on our head.
Okay.
Uh, let's see.
If you have any letters, diary, journal, or any personal items that you would ever be willing for the A&M Archives to copy, please do so.
Not asking you to give it to them, because you might want to keep them in the family.
But any time you have any papers that relate to your career, particularly as a student, and or as an employee,
and if you have any letters that you wrote home from overseas, if you would let...
I don't have any of those.
Well, does anybody in the family have any?
I doubt it.
See, my family's all family.
Because I thought if there was any V-mail or anything like that.
But if you do...
Because, you see, if we can gather all of those materials up, the more we can learn about this school, the better we can make it go in the future.
The only thing that I've got, and I will go through my salary...
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
Okay, then the last thing.
In your heart, now, as you look back, what parts of Texas A&M dearest to you?
No, but what parts of the university?
But if I were to come to you and ask...
Oh, I think engineering.
The engineering?
Any particular part of engineering?
No, I think the...
Of course, agriculture has its problems.
Or it did at that time.
It was very strong.
And you can see why.
If you want an unhappy group of people, don't feel it.
So whether you like them or don't like them, you've got to respect them.
Pierce and I were very close friends.
I liked John real well.
Former dean of business.
Hmm?
Former dean of business.
Maybe he didn't have the resources for it.
But I was...
I wasn't too impressed with Chicago.
See, I taught at SMU five years.
And they had a college division in that college.
See, they used to get all their business instructors from industry and mobile supported me to go there.
That's all we taught.
But now maybe that's changed.
See, I haven't been close to that.
But I...
I still contend that agriculture and engineering are very strong components of that system.
All right.
For today, let's stop.
And I want to thank you very, very much.
This has been a very good interview.
And I'll...
Whenever I can get a secretary, we're going to be hiring soon, get you a double-spaced first draft to go over and modify as you want to.
